  <h1>Final Paycheck Deadlines by State</h1>
  <p><em>Reviewed by our editorial team &mdash; State Wage Codes. Updated May 2026.</em></p>

  <p>Final-paycheck rules are governed by state law, and they vary substantially. Some states require payment on the date of involuntary termination (or even on the spot); others allow up to the next regular pay date. A few have no specific statutory deadline. The penalty for delayed payment also varies enormously &mdash; from California's famous waiting time penalty (up to 30 days of wages) to states with no statutory penalty at all. This reference walks through the major frameworks.</p>
  <p>State wage law changes. Confirm current statutory text and agency guidance for your state before relying on this for an actual decision.</p>

  <h2>How state final-paycheck rules typically work</h2>
  <p>Most state final-paycheck statutes distinguish between two situations:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Involuntary separation</strong> &mdash; employer-initiated termination, layoff, or end of contract. Generally has stricter deadlines.</li>
    <li><strong>Voluntary separation</strong> &mdash; employee resignation, with or without notice. Generally has more lenient deadlines, sometimes tied to notice given.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>The strictest deadlines apply to involuntary termination without notice, where the employer needs to be prepared to pay on the spot or within a very tight window. Voluntary resignation with substantial notice often allows the employer to pay on the next regular pay date.</p>

  <h2>California (Cal. Lab. Code &sect;&sect; 201&ndash;204, 203)</h2>
  <p>The most worker-protective state for final-paycheck timing:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Involuntary termination:</strong> all wages due must be paid immediately upon termination (same day).</li>
    <li><strong>Voluntary resignation with 72+ hours notice:</strong> all wages due on the last day of work.</li>
    <li><strong>Voluntary resignation without 72 hours notice:</strong> all wages due within 72 hours of resignation.</li>
    <li><strong>Penalty:</strong> waiting time penalty of daily wages &times; days late, capped at 30 days. Applies to "willful" failure to pay (a low bar).</li>
    <li><strong>Accrued vacation/PTO:</strong> treated as wages. Must be paid out at separation. "Use it or lose it" vacation policies are illegal in California.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Texas (Texas Payday Act, Tex. Labor Code Ch. 61)</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Involuntary termination:</strong> wages due within 6 days of termination, or the next regular pay date (whichever comes first).</li>
    <li><strong>Voluntary resignation:</strong> next regular pay date.</li>
    <li><strong>Penalty:</strong> the Texas Workforce Commission can assess interest plus an administrative penalty for non-payment; the Payday Act allows recovery through agency claim or private suit, with limited statutory penalty structure.</li>
    <li><strong>Accrued vacation/PTO:</strong> payout at separation depends on employer policy. Texas does not statutorily require vacation payout.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>New York (NY Lab. Law &sect;&sect; 191, 198)</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Manual workers</strong> (typically blue-collar): must be paid weekly, with final wages due no later than the regular pay date for the period in which the work was performed.</li>
    <li><strong>Clerical and other workers:</strong> at least semi-monthly, with final wages due no later than the next regular pay date.</li>
    <li><strong>Penalty:</strong> unpaid wages plus liquidated damages equal to 100% of the unpaid amount (doubling the recovery), plus attorney's fees. Liquidated damages can be avoided by employer showing good-faith basis.</li>
    <li><strong>Frequency penalty:</strong> NY also has specific penalty for failing to pay manual workers weekly &mdash; even if total wages are eventually paid, the late frequency itself is a violation.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Massachusetts (M.G.L. c. 149, &sect; 148)</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Involuntary termination:</strong> all wages due on the last day of work.</li>
    <li><strong>Voluntary resignation:</strong> next regular pay date.</li>
    <li><strong>Penalty:</strong> automatic treble damages (3x the unpaid wages) plus attorney's fees. The treble-damages structure is mandatory, not discretionary &mdash; making Massachusetts one of the most worker-protective states for wage claims.</li>
    <li><strong>Accrued vacation:</strong> if the employer's policy promises vacation, it must be paid out at separation.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Florida</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>No specific statutory final-paycheck deadline. Wages are due on the next regular pay date.</li>
    <li>No statutory penalty for delayed final payment beyond breach-of-contract damages.</li>
    <li>Florida has been one of the lighter-touch states on final-paycheck enforcement.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Illinois (Illinois Wage Payment and Collection Act)</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Final paycheck:</strong> due at the time of separation if practicable, otherwise on the next regular pay date.</li>
    <li><strong>Penalty:</strong> 2% per month interest on unpaid wages, plus statutory damages and attorney's fees.</li>
    <li><strong>Accrued vacation:</strong> generally must be paid out at separation under an Illinois Supreme Court interpretation.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Washington (RCW 49.48)</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Final paycheck:</strong> due on the next regular pay date.</li>
    <li><strong>Penalty:</strong> for willful violations, double the unpaid wages plus attorney's fees.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Colorado (Colo. Rev. Stat. &sect; 8-4-109)</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Involuntary termination:</strong> all wages due immediately, unless the accounting department isn't open, in which case within 24 hours of when it next opens (and not more than 6 hours after the start of the next workday).</li>
    <li><strong>Voluntary resignation:</strong> next regular pay date.</li>
    <li><strong>Penalty:</strong> up to 125% of wages for first 60 days late, then up to 50% per pay period; treble damages possible for repeat violators.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Oregon (ORS 652.140)</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Involuntary termination:</strong> wages due the next business day.</li>
    <li><strong>Voluntary resignation with 48+ hours notice:</strong> wages due on the last day.</li>
    <li><strong>Voluntary resignation without notice:</strong> wages due within 5 business days or on the next regular pay date.</li>
    <li><strong>Penalty:</strong> waiting time penalty similar in structure to California's &mdash; continued wages for up to 30 days for willful non-payment.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Other notable states (briefly)</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Minnesota:</strong> involuntary termination same-day; voluntary next pay date; penalty up to 15 days additional wages.</li>
    <li><strong>Hawaii:</strong> involuntary termination at end of last working day; voluntary next pay date; small statutory penalty.</li>
    <li><strong>Montana:</strong> involuntary termination same day; voluntary next pay date; statutory penalty.</li>
    <li><strong>Pennsylvania:</strong> next regular pay date; limited statutory penalty.</li>
    <li><strong>Ohio:</strong> next regular pay date; limited statutory penalty.</li>
    <li><strong>Georgia:</strong> next regular pay date; limited statutory penalty.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>How to use this reference</h2>
  <p>First, identify the state where the work was performed (not where the employer is headquartered). Second, identify whether the separation was voluntary or involuntary. Third, find your state above and check the controlling deadline and penalty structure. Fourth, if the actual payment date exceeds the deadline, use our <a href="/">calculator</a> or our <a href="/guides/how-late-pay-penalties-are-calculated/">step-by-step penalty calculation guide</a> to estimate the amount.</p>
  <p>For practical advice on what to do when you've been paid late, see <a href="/guides/what-to-do-if-paid-late/">What to do if you've been paid late</a>. For common errors in late-pay analysis, see <a href="/guides/common-late-pay-misconceptions/">Common late-pay misconceptions</a>.</p>
